==Early discoveries of brown dwarfs==
Although Kelu-1 is among the first free-floating L dwarfs discovered, it is actually not the first. Three free-floating L dwarfs were found by Xavier Delfosse et al. using the [[Deep Near-Infrared Survey of the Southern Sky|DENIS]] survey (the article was submitted and published in the same 1997, but it was submitted earlier than Ruiz et al. (1997)):{{r|Delfosse1997}}
*[[DENIS-P J020529.0-115925]]
*[[DENIS-P J1058.7-1548]]
*[[DENIS-P J1228.2-1547]]

And one free-floating L dwarf was announced by Kirkpatrick et al. using [[Two Micron All-Sky Survey|2MASS]] prototype observations ("MASP") (the article was submitted in 1996 and published in 1997):{{r|Kirkpatrick1997}}
*[[2MASP J0345432+254023]]

In addition, several free-floating brown dwarfs candidates have been found in the [[Pleiades cluster]] by Rebolo et al. (1996).{{r|Ruiz1997}}

Two early discoveries of not free-floating L and T dwarfs:
*[[Gliese 229 B]] (a T6.5-{{r|Burgasser2002}}type companion to a [[red dwarf]], detected in 1995 by Nakajima et al.){{r|Nakajima1995}}
*[[GD 165 B]] (an L4-{{r|Kirkpatrick1999}}type companion to a [[white dwarf]], detected in 1988 by Becklin and Zuckerman){{r|Becklin1988}}

Furthermore, some of late M-type stars are also considered as brown dwarfs now. Such objects were known even earlier: some of them were included to the [[NLTT]] Catalogue in 1979, for example, [[LP 944-020]].

