The '''Vogt–Russell theorem''' states that the structure of a star, in hydrostatic and thermal equilibrium with all energy derived from nuclear reactions, is uniquely determined by its mass and the distribution of chemical elements throughout its interior.<ref>{{cite book| last1= Carroll| first1=Bradley W.| last2=Ostlie| first2=Dale A.| last-author-amp=yes| title=An Introduction to Modern Astrophysics| publisher=[[Addison-Wesley]]| date=28 July 2006| page=333| edition=Second| isbn=978-0805304022}}</ref> Although referred to as a theorem, the Vogt–Russell theorem has never been formally proved. The theorem is named after astronomers [[Heinrich Vogt (astronomer)|Heinrich Vogt]] and [[Henry Norris Russell]], who devised it independently.

